<sn><md>Starts and Constellations {.text-end .text-secondary}

 :::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2016/08/082416_TO_proxima_centauri_main.jpg)
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Stars

* **Definition:** Terrestrial/celestial bodies that `possess light of their own`.
* **Composition:** Burning gasballs `made of hydrogen and helium gases` burning at extremely high temperatures (around `6000°` Celsius).
* **Visibility:** Only a few thousand are visible to the naked eye. Others require powerful telescopes. They are invisible during the day due to the `scorching light` of the Sun.
* **Distance Measurement:** Because distances are too vast to be measured in kilometers, scientists use *light years*.
* *One Light Year:* The `distance light covers in one year`. Light travels at approximately 3 lakh ($300,000$) kilometers per second.
* *Sun to Earth:* It takes light `8 minutes and 19 seconds` to reach Earth from the Sun.
* *Proxima Centauri:* The closest star to the Sun, located about `4.2 light years away` from Earth.
:::
:::



:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-8
#### Constellations

* **Definition:** `Groups of stars that appear together` in specific patterns when viewed from Earth at night.
* **Naming:** Ancient astrologers ++named++ them based on their `appearance`, often `resembling animals or figures like a bear or hunter`.
* **Examples:** Great Bear, Orion, Cassiopeia, Little Bear, and Canis Major.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-4
![img](https://starwalk.space/gallery/images/zodiac-constellations/1920x1080.jpg)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>Large Scale Structures {.text-secondary}

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSi0O__gGiB-RHLOjEOQgT7WWs3tlbaD8J1MTevAlfxFDU5bWWxqdRM42s&amp;s=10)

:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Galaxy

* **Definition:** A massive system or ++star world++ composed of `planets, stars, dust, comets, and vapours`.
* **Scale:** There are roughly `100 billion galaxies` in space, moving at great distances from each other.
* **Forms:** They `vary in size and shape`; most are ++snakelike++ (`large` in size) or ++parabolic++ (very `bright`).
* **The Milky Way:** The specific `galaxy in which we live`. In the *dark winter night sky*, it looks like a `long, bright radiance clustering in millions`, showing `vivid radiant rays from north to south`.
:::
:::



:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-8
#### Nebula

* **Definition:** An `interstellar structure` in outer space with a `peculiar appearance`.
* **Characteristics:** They are located at wide distances and can `contain millions of stars`. Nebulae can be `composed of gases or the remnants of dead stars`, and they serve as `active regions where new stars are born`. There are almost `2000 nebulae` in the solar system.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-4
![img](https://storage.noirlab.edu/media/archives/images/screen/noao0307a.jpg)
:::
